04705nam a22006975i 9780814759745DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147597457 a10.18574/nyu/9780814759745.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548380  a(OCoLC)779828207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE748.F58 M 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a320.520921 aMoser, John E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRight Turn :bJohn T. Flynn and the Transformation of American Liberalism /cJohn E. Moser. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Irish Exaggerations -- t2. Business Must Be Governed -- t3. An Empty Collection of Syllables -- t4. Pay as We Fight -- t5. A Pretty Sorry Board -- t6. A Plague of Promisers -- t7. A Great and Grand Guy—Once -- t8. A Very Responsible Committee -- t9. The Nazi Transmission Belt -- t10. The Good Name of a Noble Cause -- t11. The Smear Offensive -- t12. A Bitter and Disheartening Struggle -- t13. God Bless Joe McCarthy -- t14. It Sickens My Soul -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn T. Flynn, a prolific writer, columnist for the New Republic, Harper's Magazine, and Collier's Weekly, radio commentator, and political activist, was described by the New York Times in 1964 as “a man of wide-ranging contradictions.” In this new biography of Flynn, John E. Moser fleshes out his many contradictions and profound influence on U.S. history and political discourse.In the 1930s, Flynn advocated extensive regulation of the economy, the breakup of holding companies, and heavy taxes on the wealthy. A mere fifteen years later he was denouncing the New Deal as “creeping socialism,” calling for an abolition of the income tax, and hailing Senator Joseph McCarthy and his fellow anticommunists as saviors of the American Republic. Yet throughout his career he insisted that he had remained true to the principles of liberalism as he understood them.It was America's political culture that changed, he argued, and not his values and views. Drawing on Flynn’s life and his prolific writings, Moser illuminates how liberalism in America changed during the mid-twentieth century and considers whether Flynn’s ideological odyssey was the product of opportunism, or the result of a set of deep-seated principles that he championed consistently over the years. In addition, Right Turn examines Flynn’s role in laying the foundations for the “culture war” that would be played out in American society for the rest of the century, helping to define modern American conservatism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConservatismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJournalistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aLiberalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical activistszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475700040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814759745.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759745/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aP